Figure 1: Overall view of the data

Here, the primary aim is to visually present our priors and the RECOVERY. I believe it is extremely important to present this data in a figure since they are the foundation underlying the posterior distributions in the next figures.

Point estimates depict the median. Interval bars depict the 50th and 95th quantiles.



Figure 2: Posterior distributions

In my opinion, this is the most important figure. I decided not to use tables, because there are too much data and Panel B and D seem to handle well this great amount of data.

Panels A and C: Point estimates depict the median. Interval bars depict the 50 and 95% credible intervals. Panels B and D: Cumulative posterior distributions correspond to the probabilities that the risk difference (RD) is less than or equal to the effect size on the X‐axis.



Figure 3: Posterior distributions; Sensitivity analysis of “invasive mechanical ventilation”

This sensitivity analysis are the ones with the greatest change across priors. These changes can actually interfer clinical decision. Thus, I judged that these analyses “deserve” their own figure.

Point estimates depict the median. Interval bars depict the 50 and 95% credible intervals.
